# Next.js App Router Error/Suspense Boundaries

Apply these rules when editing route segment files in `src/app/`.

## Segment-Level Boundaries

- Use `loading.tsx` only for route-segment-level loading fallbacks.
- Use `error.tsx` only for route-segment-level error fallbacks.
- `error.tsx` must include the `"use client"` directive.
- Do not rely on route-level boundaries when only a subsection is async.

## Granular Streaming in `page.tsx`

- Keep inline `<Suspense>` boundaries in `page.tsx` for component-level streaming.
- Wrap async sections by the visual loading sequence, not by arbitrary component depth.
- Pair each async Suspense region with a localized error boundary when that region can fail independently.

## Route-Level Blocking Is A Fallback

- Use top-level route segment `loading.tsx`/`error.tsx` as the primary fallback only when the page cannot render meaningful UI without one blocking fetch.

## Example Pattern in `page.tsx`

```tsx
<ErrorBoundary fallback={<OrdersErrorFallback />}>
  <Suspense fallback={<OrdersTableSkeleton />}>
    <OrdersTableAsync />
  </Suspense>
</ErrorBoundary>
```
